2. DESIGN REFERENCES — clean-room (recorded for provenance)
====================================================================

The following were used as DESIGN references only: the code was reimplemented
from public specifications (RFCs) or from the authors' own projects (bxp, axp
= Apache-2.0, relicensed by their copyright holder to MIT here; poc-wf-analytic
= same authors). No third-party source was copied. Listed with their upstream
license so any future line-level reuse is attributed correctly. A provenance
audit is pending before any public release.

  netaddr    — RFC 6724, RFC 5952 (specs); cross-checked vs Go net/addrselect
               (BSD-3-Clause, The Go Authors) + glibc getaddrinfo algorithm.
               The CIDR/prefix operations (Prefix, summarize, mergePrefixes)
               model after Go net/netip.Prefix (BSD-3-Clause) and go4.org/
               netipx (BSD-3-Clause) — behavior only, clean-room, no source
               consulted or copied.
  http       — RFC 7230/9110 (HTTP/1.1) + RFC 7541 (HPACK header compression,
               static/Huffman tables and Appendix C vectors are the RFC's own
               data) + RFC 9113 (HTTP/2 framing + stream state machine + flow
               control; RFC 7540 consulted only where it clarifies the same
               rules) + RFC 7301 (ALPN — consumed for h2-over-TLS dispatch, not
               implemented); the HTTP/2 DoS mitigations are clean-room from the
               public CVE-2023-44487 / CVE-2024-27316 advisories (behavior
               only). Conditional requests (ETag/If-* -> 304/412) are
               clean-room from RFC 9110 sec 8.8/13; the HTTP-date parser
               follows RFC 9110 sec 5.6.7 (all three formats) with the
               days-from-civil epoch conversion (Howard Hinnant's public
               algorithm). Request-body parsing is clean-room from RFC 9110
               sec 5.6.6 (Content-Type media type + parameters), the WHATWG URL
               application/x-www-form-urlencoded rules, and RFC 7578 / RFC 2046
               sec 5.1 (multipart/form-data). The Range request-header parser
               is clean-room from RFC 7233 sec 2.1 (byte-range-set); the 206
               resolution + Content-Range emitter follows RFC 7233 sec 4. The
               content-negotiation Accept parser is clean-room from RFC 9110
               sec 12.5.1 (media-range) + sec 12.4.2 (qvalue). Clean-room
               from the RFCs, no HPACK/HTTP-2/nghttp2 source consulted or
               copied; TLS via Zig std.crypto.tls.
  dns        — RFC 1035 (wire), RFC 8484 (DoH), RFC 2782 (SRV), RFC 8659
               (CAA); design ref: miekg/dns (BSD-3-Clause) + c-ares —
               behavior only, no source copied.
  router     — design ref: go-chi/chi (MIT), julienschmidt/httprouter
               (BSD-3-Clause).
  ratelimit  — design ref: golang.org/x/time/rate (BSD-3-Clause, The Go
               Authors), nginx limit_req.
  abuseguard — design ref: nginx limit_conn (BSD-2-Clause), fail2ban
               (GPL-2.0 — documented behavior only, no code consulted or
               copied).
  throttle   — design ref: golang.org/x/sync/semaphore (BSD-3-Clause, The Go
               Authors; slot semantics only), Netflix concurrency-limits
               (Apache-2.0; design notes only), SEDA (Welsh et al., SOSP '01
               paper — bounded-queue load shedding).
  security-headers — design ref: helmet.js (MIT; defaults vocabulary + the
               `csp_helmet_default` constant reproducing helmet's default
               policy VALUE as configuration data, no source copied), OWASP
               Secure Headers Project; header semantics from RFC 6797 (HSTS),
               CSP Level 3, Fetch/HTML specs (COOP/CORP/COEP), RFC 9110.
  cors       — design ref: rs/cors (Go, MIT; preflight interception + the
               origin/method/header gate semantics) and expressjs/cors (MIT;
               reflect-request-headers default); protocol semantics from the
               WHATWG Fetch standard (CORS protocol) and RFC 9110. No source
               copied.
  resilience — design ref: resilience4j (Apache-2.0; breaker state machine,
               composition order, retry semantics, semaphore Bulkhead —
               maxConcurrentCalls/maxWaitDuration/BulkheadFullException
               behavior), Polly (BSD-3-Clause; consecutive-failure count
               breaker), failsafe-go (Apache-2.0; delay/jitter policy
               shapes), AWS Architecture Blog "Exponential Backoff And
               Jitter" (Brooker, 2015; jitter taxonomy). Behavior only, no
               source copied.
  upstream   — design ref: Envoy (Apache-2.0) and HAProxy (GPL-2.0 —
               documented behavior only, no code consulted or copied)
               upstream-cluster semantics: health-checked member set,
               pluggable load-balancing policy, per-member circuit breaking
               and concurrency caps. The load-balancing algorithms
               themselves (round-robin, smooth weighted round-robin as
               popularized by nginx, least-connections, EWMA latency) are
               public, decades-old techniques; the per-upstream concurrency
               cap models resilience4j's Bulkhead (see the resilience
               entry). Behavior only, no source copied.
  openapi    — design ref: FastAPI (MIT; the generated-spec shape and
               defaults, e.g. the default "Successful Response" 200 and
               path-parameter objects), utoipa (MIT OR Apache-2.0;
               route-metadata→spec mapping); document format per the
               OpenAPI Specification 3.1.0 (Apache-2.0, OpenAPI
               Initiative). Behavior only, no source copied.

  netlink    — kernel UAPI headers (linux/netlink.h, linux/rtnetlink.h,
               linux/if_link.h, linux/if_addr.h, linux/neighbour.h,
               linux/if.h; GPL-2.0 WITH Linux-syscall-note — constants and
               struct layouts are the OS ABI) + RFC 3549 (spec); design ref:
               libmnl (LGPL-2.1; validation/framing behavior only, no source
               consulted), vishvananda/netlink (Go, Apache-2.0; typed-query
               shape only). Clean-room, no source copied.

  wireguard  — clean-room from the documented WireGuard netlink UAPI
               (uapi/wireguard.h; GPL-2.0 WITH Linux-syscall-note — the
               command/attribute/flag constants and layouts are the kernel's
               OS ABI, not copyrightable interface code) and linux/genetlink.h
               (genlmsghdr + nlctrl CTRL_CMD_GETFAMILY); design ref: wgctrl-go
               (golang.zx2c4.com/wireguard/wgctrl, MIT) and the wg tool's
               protocol usage (message-splitting/continuation behavior) —
               behavior/attribute-shape only, no source consulted or copied.

  traceroute — clean-room from the classic traceroute(8)/mtr ICMP method
               (Van Jacobson's TTL-stepping, a public technique) + RFC 792
               (ICMP message formats, via the sibling `icmp` codec) —
               behavior only, no traceroute/mtr source consulted or copied.

  aaa-gate   — extracted from the authors' axp project (axp-central/src/
               rest.zig: admin-token gate, auditMutation, AuditThrottle;
               Apache-2.0, relicensed MIT by the copyright holder); design
               ref: envoy ext_authz (Apache-2.0) and oauth2-proxy (MIT) —
               bearer-gate behavior only, no source consulted or copied;
               bearer semantics per RFC 6750, auth framework per RFC 9110.

  acme       — RFC 8555 (ACME), RFC 7515 (JWS), RFC 7638 (JWK thumbprint),
               RFC 2986 (PKCS#10), RFC 5915 (EC private keys); design ref:
               golang.org/x/crypto/acme (BSD-3-Clause, The Go Authors;
               nonce-refill/badNonce-retry + POST-as-GET client semantics),
               certbot (Apache-2.0; flow shape only). Behavior only, no
               source copied.

  kv         — design ref: Bitcask (Basho; Apache-2.0 — the published
               log-structured model: append-only CRC'd record file +
               in-memory keydir + merge/compaction; paper/design only),
               LMDB (OpenLDAP Public License) and xitdb (MIT) — embedded
               single-writer semantics only; TigerBeetle (Apache-2.0) —
               the VOPR deterministic fault-injection *approach* (simulate
               storage faults at every I/O step, assert recovery), not its
               implementation. Clean-room: behavior/approach only, no
               source consulted or copied.

  blobmsg    — extracted from the authors' axp project (axp-core/src/
               ubus.zig; Apache-2.0, relicensed MIT by the copyright
               holder); design ref: OpenWRT libubox (blob.h/blobmsg.h; ISC)
               and OpenWRT ubus (ubusmsg.h/libubus-io.c; LGPL-2.1) — wire
               format only, clean-room, no source consulted for this
               extraction and no source copied; byte-parity verified against
               `ubus -S` output on real hardware.

  ramcache   — original seed extracted from the authors' poc-wf-analytic
               (`cache.zig`; TTL + generation invalidation + byte/entry caps).
               The W-TinyLFU admission/eviction upgrade is clean-room from the
               TinyLFU paper (Einziger & Friedman, "TinyLFU: A Highly Efficient
               Cache Admission Policy") with design refs Caffeine (Apache-2.0;
               window + SLRU probation/protected structure) and ristretto (Go,
               MIT; admission anti-starvation tie-break) — algorithm/behavior
               only, no source consulted or copied.

  nftables   — clean-room from the DOCUMENTED libnftables JSON schema
               (libnftables-json(5) man page + the nftables wiki "JSON
               representation"). The module emits the stable `nft -j`
               interchange format only; libnftables itself is GPL-2.0 and was
               referenced solely as the specification of its JSON input/output
               interface — no libnftables (or other nftables) source was
               consulted or copied.

  modbus     — clean-room from the public Modbus specifications: Modbus
               Application Protocol Specification V1.1b3 + Modbus over Serial
               Line V1.02 (modbus.org, openly published and royalty-free).
               libmodbus (LGPL-2.1+) is cited as a behavior design reference
               only — no libmodbus source was consulted or copied; the
               protocol itself is the open spec.

  mqtt       — clean-room from the OASIS MQTT Version 3.1.1 specification (an
               open, royalty-free standard). mosquitto (EPL/EDL) and Eclipse
               Paho are cited as behavior design references only — no source
               was consulted or copied.

  coap       — clean-room from RFC 7252 (the Constrained Application Protocol),
               an open IETF standard: the §3 message format (header / token /
               delta-encoded options / payload), the §5.10 option registry +
               §5.4.6 class bits + §3.2 uint value format, the §6 URI ↔ options
               mapping (with RFC 3986 percent-encoding), and the §4 message
               layer (§4.2 Confirmable retransmission timers, §4.5 message-ID
               deduplication, §4.8 transmission parameters), and the §5
               request/response model (token/message-id correlation §5.3,
               piggybacked/separate responses §5.2). No third-party CoAP source
               (libcoap, aiocoap, californium, …) was consulted or copied.

  snmp       — clean-room from RFC 1157 (SNMPv1), RFC 1905/3416 (SNMPv2c
               protocol operations), RFC 2578 (SMI types) and ITU-T X.690
               (BER). net-snmp (BSD-like) is cited as a behavior reference
               only — no source was consulted or copied.

  l2disco    — clean-room from IEEE 802.1AB (LLDP) + the IEEE 802.1/802.3
               org-TLV definitions, RFC 826 (ARP), and RFC 2131/2132 (DHCP);
               the Cisco CDP frame format is a Cisco-documented / publicly
               described (reverse-engineered) format used as a behavior
               reference only. No packet-dissector source (Wireshark / lldpd /
               net-snmp / tcpdump) was consulted or copied.

  latency-stats — the streaming moment stats (min/max/mean/stddev + RFC 3550
               jitter) are from the authors' zig-fping/axp work (see the fping
               attribution above). The `Histogram` percentile support is
               clean-room from Gil Tene's HdrHistogram design (logarithmic
               bucketing with linear sub-buckets, bounded relative error);
               design refs HdrHistogram_c (BSD-2-Clause/CC0), HdrHistogram
               Java (CC0-1.0/BSD-2), and the Rust `hdrhistogram` crate
               (MIT OR Apache-2.0) — behavior/format only, no source consulted
               or copied.

  uci        — clean-room from the documented OpenWRT UCI (Unified
               Configuration Interface) file format (OpenWRT wiki/docs).
               libuci (LGPL-2.1) is referenced for the format only — no
               libuci source was consulted or copied; the file format is the
               documented interface.

  decimal    — extracted from the authors' bxp project (Apache-2.0, relicensed
               MIT). The rounding modes (half_even/half_up/half_down/up/down/
               ceiling/floor + rescale/quantize/divRound) are clean-room from
               the published definitions: Java BigDecimal.RoundingMode javadoc,
               the IBM General Decimal Arithmetic specification, and the Python
               `decimal` docs — definitions/truth-tables only, no source code
               consulted or copied.

  jwt        — clean-room from the JOSE/OAuth2 RFCs: RFC 7515 (JWS), RFC 7519
               (JWT), RFC 7517 (JWK/JWKS), RFC 7518 (JWA), RFC 8037 (EdDSA in
               JOSE), RFC 8017 (PKCS #1 v2.2), RFC 8725 (JWT BCP), OpenID
               Connect Discovery 1.0 + RFC 8414 (issuer metadata, the cached
               `Provider`), and RFC 6750 (the Bearer resource-server
               middleware; challenge/error codes). RFC known-answer vectors
               (7515 A.1/A.2/A.3, 8037 A.4) are transcribed from the RFCs for
               tests. No third-party JWT library source (jose, jsonwebtoken,
               golang-jwt, …) was consulted or copied; the signatures use
               `std.crypto`.

  http.sse   — clean-room from the WHATWG HTML "server-sent events" standard
               (the text/event-stream wire format: event/id/retry/data fields,
               multi-line data, comment lines). No third-party source consulted
               or copied.

  mcp-http   — clean-room from the Model Context Protocol "Streamable HTTP"
               transport specification (2025-06-18 revision) and the JSON-RPC
               2.0 spec; the behavioral contract (POST /mcp, Mcp-Session-Id,
               GET/DELETE, 202-for-notifications) was cross-checked against the
               authors' own bxp-gui Dart server (which wraps the third-party
               mcp_dart package) for parity — no mcp_dart or other MCP-transport
               source was consulted or copied. Builds on the sibling `mcp`
               module (JSON-RPC core, itself extracted from the authors'
               bxp-mcp).

  linkheader — clean-room from RFC 8288 (Web Linking — the `Link` header
               grammar). No third-party source consulted or copied.

  idempotency — clean-room from the Idempotency-Key pattern (Stripe's public
               API docs + the IETF draft-ietf-httpapi-idempotency-key-header).
               Behavior/semantics only; caching over the sibling `ramcache`.

  webhooksig — clean-room from RFC 2104 (HMAC) and the publicly-documented
               GitHub/Stripe webhook-signature schemes (`sha256=<hex>` over the
               body). HMAC via Zig `std.crypto`; no third-party source copied.

  tracecontext — clean-room from the W3C Trace Context Level 1 recommendation
               (`traceparent`/`tracestate`). No third-party source copied.

  cookies    — clean-room from RFC 6265 (HTTP State Management Mechanism):
               the Cookie request-header grammar (sec 5.4). No third-party
               source consulted or copied.

See each module's README "Provenance" note for its specific seed and reference.
